 culture after the ravages of the Pol Pot regime-and to bear witness to the transformation and persistence of tradition among contemporary Cambodians at home and abroad. Bringing together essays by Khmer and Western scholars in anthropology, linguistics, literature, and ethnomusicology, the volume documents the survival of a culture that many had believed lost. Individual chapters explore such topics as Buddhist belief and practice among refugees in the United States, distinctive features of modern Cambodian novels, the lessons taught by Khmer proverbs, some uses of metaphor by the Khmer Rouge regime, the state of traditional music, the recent revival of a form of traditional theater, the concept of pain in Khmer culture, changing conceptions of gender, and refugees' interpretation of American television. Together the essays map a contemporary Cambodian culture, which, for over two hundred thousand Khmers, is now firmly entwined in the social fabric of the urban West.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aKhmer (Southeast Asian people)zForeign countries. 4aAsian Studies. 4aHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aEbihara, May M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEbihara, May Mayko, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFisher-Nguyen, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoc Dy, Khing, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKalab, Milada, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLedgerwood, Judy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLedgerwood, Judy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLobban, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarcucci, J